Rome, observatory of the Capitol, lat. + 41° 53' 33"  , 6. Established in 1848; belongs to the university;
                    small transit circle and a 4 A-inch refractor by Merz. The latter is used by
                    Respighi for observations of solar prominences.

Williamstown (Massachusetts), lat. + 42° 42' 49", long. 4
                     h 52  m 33  s 5 W. Founded in 1836; 7⅜-inch refractor by Clark;
                    meridian circle of 4⅜-inches aperture by Repsold, mounted in 1882.
